stead of attaching money to the number of students enrolled, there should be an monetary attachment to the student. The school the student chooses gets the monetary attachment. Its very simple and it has worked in countries like Belgium (whose graduates succeed higher in standardized testing then the US). Buy John Stossel's book &quot;Myths, Lies, and Downright Stupidity: Get Out the Shovel--Why Everything You Know is Wrong&quot;. It has an excellent section on school chose. For those that prefer farther right commentaries: Ann Coulter's &quot;Godless&quot; has some excellent points on school choice as well. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="899" language="en" documentId="4741" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Right of Center" date="1st November 2006 01:02 AM" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.volconvo.com/forums/showthread.php?t=12481&amp;page=2" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4741" notes="" title="Public Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="300"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="301" end="899"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>